<br>
<br>
» In 1911, Turkey established for real gun control. Subsequently, from 1915 to 1917, 1.5-million Armenians, deprived of the means to defend themselves, were rounded up and killed.<br>
<br>
» Senator Diane Feinstein, speaking on &quot;60-Minutes&quot; immediately after the passage of the Brady Bill said, &quot;if I thought I could get the votes, I'd have taken them all.&quot; That's not paranoia; that is the clearly stated objective of a liberal Democrat U.S. senator.<br>
<br>
» The Soviet Union established gun control in 1929. Then from 1929 to 1953, approximately 20-millon dissidents — again, deprived of the means to defend themselves — were rounded up and killed.<br>
<br>
» April 5, 1996, Charles Krauthammer wrote in the Washington Post, &quot;the Brady Bill's only effect will be to desensitize the public to regulation of weapons in preparation for their ultimate confiscation.&quot; &quot;Ultimate,&quot; as in inevitable, eventually, sometime in the future ... not now ... BUT soon.<br>
<br>
» Forget the phony Hitler quotes, and focus on the facts. In 1938 Germany did establish gun control. From 1939 to 1945 over 13-million Jews, gypsies, homosexuals, mentally ill, union leaders, Catholics and others, unable to fire a shot in protest, were rounded up and killed.<br>
<br>
» Editor of the Boston Globe T. Winship wrote in Editor and Publisher Magazine, April 24, 1993, &quot;Investigate the NRA with renewed vigor. Print names of those who take NRA funds. Support all causes the NRA opposes. ... The work a day guy doesn't envision total confiscation, but many with the real power to sway public opinion and effect change in America do.&quot;<br>
<br>
» China has more practice than anyone does in disarming potential dissenters. Once upon a time they banned knives and swords. In 1935 they established gun control. Subsequently, between 1948 and 1952, over 20-million dissidents, again deprived of the tools for self defense, were rounded up and killed.<br>
<br>
» Democrat Representative W. Clay was quoted in the St. Louis Post Dispatch of May 8, 1993, regarding the Brady Bill. He said it is &quot;the minimum step&quot; Congress should take. &quot;We need much stricter gun control and eventually we should bar ownership of handguns except in a few cases.&quot;<br>
<br>
» Cambodia enshrined gun control in 1956. In just two years (1975-1977) over one million &quot;educated&quot; people were rounded up and killed.<br>
<br>
» Guatemala locked in gun control in 1964. From 1964 to 1981, over 100,000 Mayan Indians were rounded up and killed as a result of their inability to defend themselves.<br>
<br>
» Former President of NBC News M. Gartner was quoted in USA Today, Jan. 16, 1992, as saying, &quot;I now think the only way to control handgun use is to prohibit the guns. And the only way to do that is to change the Constitution.&quot; Hello?!<br>
<br>
» Uganda got gun control in 1970. Over the next nine years over 300,000 Christians were rounded up and killed.<br>
<br>
Peter Shields, founder of Handgun Control Inc. was quoted in the New Yorker Magazine, June 26, 1976, with what frankly crystallizes the alleged paranoia many of us have for preserving the Second Amendment. <br>
<br>
&quot;We'll take one step at a time, and the first is necessarily ... given the political realities ... very modest. We'll have to start working again to strengthen the law, and then again to strengthen the next law and again and again. Our ultimate goal, total control of handguns, is going to take time. The first problem is to make possession of all handguns and ammunition (with a few exceptions) totally illegal.&quot;<br>
<br>
 <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=148213">Kellianne</a>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uradgen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Radgen</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/misc_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 293<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/9/02 5:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=187.topic&index=89>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://radgen.homestead.com/files/Radgen5.jpg height=150 width=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Gun Control and Crime, the English experience</span><hr size=1> It is paranoia.  Of course there are going to be people who want to ban all firearms  You managaed to quote ONE Senator out of 100 and ONE representative out of 435.  Just as there are people who want to lift all restrictions on firearms.  That does not make either position a realistic possibility.<br>
<br>
So where are the massive stomping of human rights on a defenseless population in the 100 other countries with strict gun control?   Gun control does not equal dictatorship.  Obviously most Dictatorships HAVE strict gun control (but even this is not universal) but so do most democracies.  There is no correlation between gun control laws and the oppressiveness of the government.  ALL kinds of governments have gun control oppresive, free, weak or strong.<br>
<br>
You right wingnuts are falling into a trap.  Fighting tooth and nail against every single effort that even remotely might impact firearms is playing into the hands of the left wingnuts.  If there ever is a successgul effort at a general ban, the blame falls squarely on the gun lobby and its absolute refusal to reasonable compromise.<br>
<br>
Ever wonder how Prohibition came into being when it was obvious from the start that it did not have anywhere near the support of the majority of the population?  One of the reasons was the brewing industries arrogance.  The problems that the temperance organizations were complaining about were real.  But the brewing industry fought tooth and nail against attempts at addressing these issues in a reasonable manner.  The argument soon became one of do nothing or Prohibition because of the inability of BOTH sides to compromise.  Doing nothing was not an option so we got Prohibition.  It was a huge mistake but the brewing industry was as much to blame for its inception as was the extremeist temperance organizations who pushed for it in the first place.<br>
<br>
There are very real problems with the easy availibilty of firearms in this country.   I oppose anything resembeling a ban.  BUT I am not blind to the carnage that firearms cause in this country.  None of our basic rights are absolute.  Their are limits on all of them.  Generally speaking you can't impact someone elses rights in the persuit of your rights.  In these very strictly limited cases, the government can regulate.  Freedom of Speech but you can't yell &quot;Fire!!!&quot; in a crowded movie theatre is the best example.<br>
<br>
Now with the second amendment, the right to bear arms is assured, BUT there are situations where someone bearing arms is a immeadiate and clear threat to someone else's rights (usually life or liberty)  The debate should be how do we better control THAT situation without stepping on the rights of those who do NOT pose a threat to the basic rights of those around them.  How do we better control the flow of firearms into the criminal world without impacting possesion by law-abiding citizens.  There is an answer out there, but until both the right wing and left wing nuts get off there soapboxes and back off thier extremeist positons, we will never find one.<br>
<br>
Personally I would rather they lift ALL restrictions on firearms  (You want to own a howitzer, no problem) but have a robust registration system with teeth.  It is the transfer from legal market to illegal market that is allows criminals to so easily get hold of weapons.  We need to start controling THAT transfer better.  You cannot do it unless the government(state. local of federal) can better track gun ownership.   Even then it will take years of effective enforcement to shrink the supply of guns on the black market, but it can be done.<br>
<br>
One other thing. Simple registration, probably is not unconstitutional because as long as it does not itself disallow gun ownership.  However licsensing gun ownership is another matter.  The term inherently implies a standard needs to be met.  This IS a restriction.  As much as I would like to make sure that everyone who owns a gun knows how to safely use it, I don't think the case can be made that there is enough compelling interest for the government to restrict a basic right in this way except in most extreme cases (i.e no felons, mental patients etc.  Cases where there is a high likelyhood of someone else's right to life is at stake)<br>
<br>
So in the end, I don't believe that a registration requirement is out of reach, I do think that licsensing DOES run into constitutional problems. <p><center><font face="lucida handwriting, arial" color="006800" size=+2><b>Radgen Waldjaeger</font></b><br><font face="tempus sans ITC, arial" color="675f00" size=+1><b>Retired Pathfinder of Karana</font><br><font face="tempus sans ITC, arial" color="blue" size=+1>Shining Path</font></b><br><img src=http://radgen.homestead.com/files/tiger_run_md_clr.gif></center>
